<table align="center" width="900" cellspacing="1"  cellpadding="10" border="0" bgcolor="#FFFFF0">
<tr>
<td><div>
      
<font size="+4" color=#990000>The infinitive</font> is form of the verb that 
has no reference to a tense. It is not present, past, or future.<br><br>

<font size="+4" color=#990000>In English</font>, infinitives <strong>start</strong> with "to":<br>

<table align="center" cellpadding=20">
<tr bgcolor="#E0F0F5">
<td><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>to</strong></font> study, 
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>to</strong></font> eat</font>, 
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>to</strong></font> write</div></td>
</tr>

</table>
<br>
<font size="+4" color=#990000>In Spanish</font>, infinitives <strong>end</strong> in "ar", "er" or "ir":<br>

<table align="center" cellpadding=20">
<tr bgcolor="#E0F0F5">
<td><div>estudi<font color="#3915B4"><strong>ar</strong></font>, 
com<font color="#3915B4"><strong>er</strong></font>, 
escrib<font color="#3915B4"><strong>ir</strong></font></div></td>
</tr>

</table>


<br>
The "ar", "er" and "ir" are called <strong>endings</strong>.  The rest is called the <strong>stem</strong>.  <br><br>


<font size="+4" color="#EE871B">Verbs have stems and endings</font> 

</font>
